Introduction¶

This project is conducted as a part of Udacity Data Analyst Nanodegree. The purpose of this project is to perform exploratory data analysis, then create a presentation with explanatory charts that conveys findings and insights from the data set provided.

The studied data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan provided by Prosper Marketplace, California-based pioneering company in the peer-to-peer lending industry in the U.S. Since its establishment in 2005, Prosper has helped more than 1.3 million customers get access to over $21 billion in affordable loans (source)

Each loan includes loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), loan status, borrower income, and many others. This data dictionary contains specific details on every single dataset's variable.

In this analysis, I am focusing on the main research question of what factors affect the borrowing interest rate?

# Create a list of columns corresponding to this analysis
analyzed_vars=['ListingKey','Term', 'LoanStatus', 'BorrowerAPR','BorrowerRate', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'ProsperScore', 
               'ListingCategory (numeric)', 'EmploymentStatus','IncomeRange', 'StatedMonthlyIncome','LoanOriginalAmount', 
               'LoanOriginationDate','MonthlyLoanPayment']
# Create the new dataframe used for analyzing
df_reduced_vars = df.loc[:,analyzed_vars]

Some variables require the transformation on their data types. Specifically, I should convert IncomeRange and ProsperRating (Alpha) to be ordinal types since they have intrinsic ranking order in their natures.

To be more specific, Prosper Rating is Prosper's estimation of borrower's estimated loss rate which is determined based on two scores: (1) the credit score, obtained from an official credit reporting agency, and (2) the Prosper Score, figured in-house based on the Prosper population. Prosper ratings are labeled AA, A, B, C, D, E, and HR, with AA being related to the lowest-risk customers.

Besides, ListingCategory, BorrowerState, and EmploymentStatus should be converted into categories while LoanOriginationDate will be reset as datetime variable.

In [5]:
# Convert ordinal variables into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'IncomeRange':['$0','$1-24,999','$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$75,000-99,999','$100,000+'],
                    'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['HR','E','D','C', 'B', 'A', 'AA']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    df_reduced_vars[var] = df_reduced_vars[var].astype(ordered_var)

Overvew of dataset for further exploration¶

What is the structure of dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113937 rows and 16 columns, including both quantitative and qualitative variables. In term of qualitative variables, there are both ordinal and nominal categorical variables with the following stages for ordinal ones (lowest) > (highest):

Income range: 0, 1-24,999, 25,000-49,999, 50,000-74,999, 75,000-99,999, 100,000+

ProsperRating: HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA

What are the main features of interest in this dataset?¶

I would like to discover what are the major features for predicting the borrower interest rate of loan in the dataset.

What features in the dataset will help support the investigation into the features of interest?¶

I presume that customer risk score and income will have the most significant influences on each loan interest rate. In Prosper Marketplace system, a custom risk score is built using its historical data. The score ranges from 1-11, with 11 being the best, or lowest risk score. Interchangeably, Prosper rating scale varies from HR to AA, with AA being the lowest risk credit rating customers. Bearing that idea in mind, the relationships I expect from my discovery is that the higher credit rating and income the borrowers get, the better outcomes they will acquire for their loans in terms of interest rate.

Additionally, I'm also interested in the effects of, for example, Listing Category and Employment Status on loan borrowing rate outcomes.

BorrowerAPR is the Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan which is generally equal or higher than the BorrowerRate since it includes not only interest rate but also all the service fees applicable.

# Add functions for facilitating plot drawing to avoid code repetition on the exploration

def x_y_t(xaxis,yaxis,title):
    '''
   Function that return any chart title and its X-axis, Y-axis
    '''
    plt.xlabel(xaxis,size=10)
    plt.ylabel(yaxis,size=10)
    plt.title(title,size=13);
    
def plot_hist_charts(binsize,col):
    '''
   Function that return histogram for continuous variable with its correspondingly proper binsize
    '''
    bins = np.arange(col.min(), col.max()+binsize,binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
    plt.hist(col,bins=bins)
    
def plot_log_charts(log_binsize,col):
    '''
   Function that return log transformation histogram for continuous variable with its correspondingly proper binsize
    '''
    # Condition to handle the case when a variable takes zero values and can't get logarithmic transformation
    # but need adding value 1 to all the values in that variable to make log transformation legitimate.
    if col.min()==0:
        col_new=col+1
        bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(col_new.min()), np.log10(col_new.max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
    else:
        bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(col.min()), np.log10(col.max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
    plt.hist(col,bins=bins)
    plt.xscale('log')

In regards to loan status, approximately 57 thousands, equivalent to half amount of loan transactions are currently on-going which we don't know yet either it would be defaulted or not. In term of employment status, employed customers constitutes 60% of Prosper borrowers while only less than 1% of Prosper customers are unemployed.

When it comes to listing category, half of borrowers listed the purpose of their loan applications is to consolidate a debt which is a type of loan used to combine all the existing debts into one pot at a lower interest rate. The second and third biggest amount of loan applications fall into 'Not Available' and 'Other' categories with 15% and 9% respectively. The next two most popular listing categories are home improvement with 6.5% and business with 6.3% .

Loan Origination Year experiences a decrease in 2009 in amount of loans before it started increasing progressively and reached its peak in 2013.

BorrowerRate and Borrower APR are highly correlated since Borrower APR includes BorrowerRate and all service fees applicable.

The second most positive significant relationship is between loan original amount and monthly loan payment. This makes sense in the mechanism that the higher loan amount customers borrow, the greater amount each month they expect to pay.

As expected, the correlation coefficient between Borrower APR and Prosper score is strongly negative. Since Prosper score is a measure of customer credit risk, it's not surprising that the lower prosper score borrowers get, the more expensive interest rate they are supposed to obtain for their loans.

Another seemingly interesting negative correlation is between borrower interest rate and original amount of loan. It appears that with the higher sum of original loan, Prosper customer has a tendency to receive a more favorable borrowing rate.

Similar to monthly loan payment, term is also positively corrected with loan original amount. This is not much of suprise since customers are more likely to opt for the greater length of loan when they borrow a bigger sum of money. In that way, the amount they have to pay monthly will deliver a smaller effect on their monthly budget.

Finally, we see positive correlations between stated monthly income with amount of original loan and monthly loan payment. These relationships could be explained in the way that customers with more stable monthly income can be approved with higher bulk of original loan and monthly loan payment.

# Compute the logarithm of Loan Original Amount to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ Function to compute log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

df_reduced_vars['log_loan_amount'] = df_reduced_vars['LoanOriginalAmount'].apply(log_trans)

Summary of bivariate exploration¶

Some of the main relationships I have observed in this part of the investigation. How do the features of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

BorrowerRate and Borrower APR have a surprisingly high amount of correlation. The reason is because Borrower APR includes BorrowerRate and all yearly service fees applicable.

A significant negative linear relationship is found between Borrower APR and Prosper score. This correlation appears to be in line with our expectation. Since customer credit score is a measure of customer credit risk, it's not surprising that the lower prosper score borrowers are assessed, the more expensive interest rate they are supposed to obtain for their loans.

There appears also seemingly interesting negative correlation between borrower interest rate and original amount of loan. Prosper customers who got a bigger loan amount are associated with decreasing annual interest rate. One of the reasonably explanatory factor is the fact that customers approved bigger amount of loan are also associated with cheaper loans due to their trustworthy credit scores. This worths further investigating in the upcoming multivariate exploration section.

Finally, bivariate exploration depicts that past due, chargedoff, and defaulted loans generally have higher interest rates. On the contrary, completed loans seem to be the ones that have the lowest interest rate.

Any interesting relationships between the other features observed?¶

Monthly loan payment and term are positively corrected with loan original amount. This can be explained due to the fact that the bigger loan amount customers receive, the more considerable monthly loan amount and longer period of months they are supposed to pay back their loans.
